thread.title: Blue Jays survive, win Game 3 of ALDS vs. Rangers
thread.title_full: Blue Jays survive, win Game 3 of ALDS vs. Rangers

author: tennessean
title: Blue Jays survive, win Game 3 of ALDS vs. Rangers
text:
ARLINGTON, Texas — Toronto Blue Jays right-hander Marco Estrada lived dangerously all season. He induced few ground balls and struck out few hitters, meaning the ball was repeatedly struck in the air in a home ballpark highly conducive to home runs.
Few found the fences during the season — Estrada had a sparkling 3.13 ERA to go with his 13-8 record — and, in fact, few balls even found the turf against a stingy defense, as opponents had a worse batting average on balls in play against him, .217, than any other starter.
In other words, Estrada can pitch with the confidence that nearly every ball hit behind him will get caught. Toronto’s fielders were their reassuring best in Sunday’s American League Division Series Game 3 victory, as too was the heart of its vaunted lineup.
Behind 6 1/3 innings of one-run ball from Estrada, the Jays won 5-1 to avoid a sweep in their first postseason appearance in 22 seasons, though the Rangers still lead two games to one.
Toronto shortstop Troy Tulowitzki slugged a three-run homer in the sixth inning that made up for several early squanders, as the Jays hit into four double plays, all with runners in scoring position and two with the bases loaded. Their first two runners to cross the plate did so without the benefit of a run-scoring hit, plating them on one of those double plays and a walk.
For Tulowitzki, who missed two weeks in late September with a broken bone near his shoulder, the blast was his first hit in 11 tries this series. Asked about his struggles before the game, Blue Jays manager John Gibbons said, “Well, he's not getting a lot of hits, but nobody in the middle of our lineup is getting a lot of hits.”
No longer. Josh Donaldson had two hits and a walk, Edwin Encarnacion had two walks, Bautista singled and Tulowitzki went 2-for-3 with a walk, reversing the fortunes of the Big Four. They went 5-for-12 with two extra-base hits after going 5-for-35 with one extra-base hit in the first two games.
USA TODAY
Adrian Beltre not in Rangers lineup for Game 3 of ALDS
Estrada, who struck out four and walked none, had the outfield supporting him in grand fashion: center fielder Kevin Pillar caught a deep flyball while crashing into the wall in the second inning, and left fielder Ben Revere tracked down a deep gap shot to end the fourth. Both saved extra-base hits.
At face value, some of the advanced metrics attribute much of Estrada’s season results to good fortune — he even walks more batters than anyone else in his starting staff — although the staunch defense ought to receive plenty of credit.
In fact, those numbers would have you believe that Estrada might, in fact, be the luckiest pitcher in all of baseball. His starting counterpart, Rangers lefthander Martin Perez, ranked as the unluckiest by comparing each’s season ERA with his Fielding-Independent Pitching, which normalizes ERA for an average defense.
Estrada exceeds his statistical projection with his pitch variance, as he mixes his average fastball (90 mph) with a good changeup, curve and cutter to minimize damage. He tied for fourth in the AL in the most soft contact — 21.4% of batted balls, according to FanGraphs.
Perez also didn’t get the same fielding aid as Estrada, as his center fielder, Delino DeShields, misplayed a ball that looked a lot like the one Pillar snared, only this became a leadoff double from Toronto’s Dioner Navarro in the second. Similarly, Donaldson led off the fourth with a sinking liner deep into the right-center gap that just eluded DeShields’ dive for a double. Both later scored.
Not all of it is just luck, however. Perez did not help his own cause with his wildness. After Donaldson’s double, Perez issued a one-out intentional walk to Edwin Encarnacion, which he followed up with two unintentional walks to Chris Colabello and Troy Tulowitzki to give up a run. Those three Toronto walks were as many as it had in the first two games combined; Tulowtizki hadn’t reached base except on an error in his 11 at bats this series.
USA TODAY
Rougned Odor 'fearless' for Texas Rangers, who can wrap up ALDS vs. Toronto
Perez had difficulty pitching out of the stretch all season, holding opponents to a .209 average with the bases empty but getting hit at a scorching .394 clip after a runner reached. The Rangers chose him for this assignment because his ground ball rate led the rotation and seemed like an apt fit against a Blue Jays offense that led the majors in runs and homers. Instead, the Jays scored four of their runs off Perez in five innings.
Toronto knuckleballer R.A. Dickey starts in Monday's matinee, although Gibbons hinted pre game that Game 1 and 2 starters, David Price and Marcus Stroman, could be available early in relief. The Rangers start Derek Holland, who had a 4.91 ERA in an abbreviated season but has ample playoff experience highlighted by 8 1/3 shutout innings in Game 4 of the 2011 World Series.
